<p>===</p>
<p>Learning and studying Latin-style bass lines can be a fantastic way to develop the rhythmic side of your bass playing.</p>
<p>Latin jazz, salsa and timba all stem from Latin and African rhythms - I'm simply crazy for the stuff, and studying it has had a profound effect on my bass playing. </p>
<p>So, I thought it'd be fun to share a Latin-style bass play-along from the Academy with you... so you can give it a go yourself! </p>
<p>I've recorded a video of me performing the song as a  reference for you. You can download the backing track (without bass) and lead sheet below.</p>
<p>In case you want to investigate this style of music a little more, you need to check these bass players out: </p>
<ul>
<li>Israel “Cachao” Lopez</li>
<li>John Benitez </li>
<li>Andy Gonzalez </li>
<li>John Peña </li>
<li>Alain Perez </li>
<li>Anthony Jackson (love his playing with Michel Camillo) </li>
<li>Lincoln Goines </li>
<li>Oscar Cartaya</li>
<li>Alvaro Benavides (check him out with the Pedrito Martinez Group) </li>
<li>Panagiotis Andreou</li>
</ul>
<p>As always, see you in the shed...Scott :)</p>
